    <p class="text-sky result-sub-heading mb-4" id="li-2b">
      2.2 Your Mindset
    </p>
    <p class="font-paragraph-2 mb-2">
      Your mindset is how you see the world; it encompasses your key beliefs about how humans and organizations should function. They steer the behavior that is covered in this report!
      <br>
      To clarify further, we have defined two opposite mindsets. Both are useful and necessary in certain circumstances.
      <br/>
      The two opposite mindsets are:
    </p>
    <p class="mb-2 font-paragraph-2">
      <span class="text-sky font-weight-bold">The Closed, Controlling Mindset.</span> If you have a closed/controlling mindset, you believe things need to be structured, organized and controlled. You believe people should focus on their tasks, receive clear instructions, and that you should follow through on them.
    </p>
    <p class="mb-4 font-paragraph-2">
      <span class="text-sky font-weight-bold">The Open, Exploring Mindset.</span>  If you have an open/exploring mindset, you believe you need to trust in people and processes. You believe giving people autonomy will create energy that can then be guided in the right direction.
    </p>
    <p class="text-purple result-sub-heading-2 mb-3" id="li-3d">
      2.2.1. Mindset Meter
    </p>
    <p class="mb-5 font-paragraph-2">
      In the graph below, you can see where different categories of evaluators place you on the spectrum between Closed/Controlling and Open/Exploring extremes. So, your mindset lies somewhere in between the two! In the next section, you can see your scores on the different beliefs that relate to a Closed or Open mindset.
    </p>
    <div class="py-3">
